source: Arabic, Malay, Indonesian, Pashto, Urdu, Uyghur, Avar, Bosnian, Albanian, Dhivehi, Hausa, Swahili, Quranic
info: Arabic form of Abraham, also used in several other languages. This form appears in the Quran.

Possibly means "interpreter, teacher" in Arabic, related to the root درس (darasa) meaning "to study, to learn". According to the Quran this was the name of an ancient prophet. He is traditionally equated with the Hebrew prophet Enoch.
Means "charity, good deed" in Arabic, from the root حسن (ḥasuna) meaning "to be good".
Means "honour" in Arabic, from the root كرم (karuma) meaning "to be generous".
Arabic form of Elijah, also used in several other languages.
Alternate transcription of Arabic إلياس (see Ilyas) chiefly used in North Africa.

source: Arabic, Urdu, Punjabi, Malay, Indonesian, Bengali, Quranic
info: Arabic form of Amram, referring to the father of Moses. According to the Quran, this was also the name of the father of the Virgin Mary (analogous to the Christian Joachim).
Alternate transcription of Arabic امتياز or Urdu امتیاز (see Imtiyaz).
Means "giving, bestowal, act of kindness" in Arabic, ultimately related to نعم (naʿima) meaning "to live in comfort, to be delighted".
Means "care of Allah", derived from Arabic عناية (ʿināya) meaning "care, concern" combined with الله (Allah).
Means "fortunate" in Arabic. Allama Muhammad Iqbal (1877-1938) was a poet, philosopher, and scholar from Pakistan.
Means "guidance, direction" in Arabic, from the root رشد (rashada) meaning "to be on the right path, to be rightly guided".

source: Arabic, Persian, Albanian, Bosnian, Indonesian, Malay, Quranic
info: Arabic form of Jesus. This form is found in the Quran and is used as a given name by Muslims. Arabic-speaking Christians instead use يسوع (Yasūʿ) to refer to Jesus Christ.
Arabic, Indonesian and Malay form of Alexander.
From the name of the religion, derived from Arabic إسلام (ʾIslām) meaning "submission (to God)".
Alternate transcription of Arabic إسماعيل (see Ismail) using French orthography.

source: Arabic, Malay, Indonesian, Urdu, Bengali, Uyghur, Kyrgyz, Chechen, Avar, Kazakh, Albanian, Dhivehi, Quranic
info: Arabic form of Ishmael, also used in several other languages. According to the Quran and Islamic tradition Ismail was a prophet and the founder of the Arab people.
Derived from Arabic عصمة (ʿiṣma) meaning "safeguarding, protection, chastity, virtuousness", a derivative of عصم (ʿaṣama) meaning "to protect".
